    "summary": "The Great Persecution (303–313 AD), launched by Emperor [[event:2026|Diocletian]] and continued by his successor Galerius, was the most severe and systematic Roman persecution of Christianity — a series of four edicts that ordered the destruction of churches and Christian scriptures, the removal of Christians from government positions, the imprisonment of clergy, and ultimately the demand that all Christians sacrifice to the Roman gods under penalty of death. The persecution's ferocity varied enormously by region: in the east (under Galerius and later Maximinus), it was enforced with great brutality; in the west (under Constantius Chlorus, father of [[event:2027|Constantine]]), enforcement was minimal.\n\nThe Great Persecution lasted a decade, claimed thousands of martyrs, destroyed an enormous number of Christian texts and buildings, and created a lasting community division between those who had surrendered scriptures (traditores — literally 'those who hand over,' the origin of the word 'traitor') and those who had not. The schism between the Donatists (rigorists who refused to accept the authority of clergy who had capitulated) and the mainstream church haunted North African Christianity for over a century and required [[event:2029|Constantine's]] intervention. Ironically, the Great Persecution was followed almost immediately by the most dramatic reversal in Roman religious history: Constantine's conversion, the [[event:2028|Edict of Milan]] (313 AD), and within two generations the complete Christianization of the Roman state under [[event:2031|Theodosius I]]. The Church that survived persecution became the Church of the empire.",
